WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.600
 Welcome to chapter four, Functions and Program Structure.

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:08.440
 In this chapter, we're going to start digging a little deeper.

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:11.520
 Part of the goal of this course is to get you to the point

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:14.240
 where we can talk about how things really work.

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:16.600
 Eventually, in the next course, we'll even go down

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:19.640
 to hardware and architecture and gates.

00:00:19.640 --> 00:00:22.680
 And so it's time to start opening things up

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:24.640
 and looking at how things work.

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:26.920
 And so this is a good time to do so.

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:29.020
 And the big thing we're gonna learn, among other things,

00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:33.600
 is the concept of a stack, how pass-by-reference works,

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:37.520
 how pass-by-value and pass-by-reference work,

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:38.920
 a little bit about recursion.

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:42.440
 Recursion's a thing that I worry about a lot.

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:45.560
 Well, we'll get there.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:47.560
 And preprocessors, these are all things

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:50.000
 where we're really starting, it's not so much

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:51.800
 about just how functions work,

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:54.700
 but how functions are implemented

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:57.840
 and how that affects how they work.

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:00.040
 So the first thing I wanna talk to you about

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:04.000
 is a really nifty computer science concept called a stack.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
 A stack is a data structure that we use

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.920
 and it has a couple of attributes.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:15.380
 The idea of a stack is we start with an empty stack

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:17.960
 and we put things on the stack and then we take things off.

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:20.640
 We take them off, the last thing we put on

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:21.800
 is the first thing we get off.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:23.440
 And they go up and they go down.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:27.160
 You can push things onto them and take things off of them.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:29.780
 We can approximate this with a Python list.

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:31.160
 So we start with an empty list.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:33.120
 We append the string one to it

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:34.760
 and the stack has a one on it.

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:36.960
 It's kind of growing up from the bottom

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:38.340
 and it's gonna shrink from the top.

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:40.600
 And then we append a two to it

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.160
 and then our stack is now one and two.

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:45.120
 So the bottom thing in the stack is one

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:46.720
 and the top one is two.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.480
 And then we append a three to it

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:50.760
 and we have one, two, three on the stack.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:52.360
 At that point, we pop.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:56.020
 Pop says, give me the most recent pushed thing

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:57.380
 and then take it off.

00:01:57.380 --> 00:02:01.480
 So we pop off three and the stack remains with one and two.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:04.680
 Again, this is also known as the last in, first out

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.240
 or LIFO queue.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:07.680
 Queue is like a line of things.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.640
 And so the last thing in is the first thing you got out.

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:13.200
 So that's a stack and we're gonna use stacks

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:14.660
 in function calls.

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:18.640
 So historically, when we talk about call by value

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:20.040
 and call by reference,

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:23.440
 we basically say that call by value means that somehow

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:26.480
 this value like in the main program MA with a variable

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:30.720
 with a value 42 ends up being copied into the function

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:35.720
 and the parameter OP has got a copy of the 42.

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:39.680
 It's not the original MA, it's the copy of 42.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:42.480
 So 42 gets passed in the function one

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:44.480
 and OP is a copy of 42.

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:48.360
 So then inside the function, we can subtract 10 from it

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:51.220
 and then we can see that.

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:52.800
 But then when we get back in the main function,

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.640
 we see that MA has been unchanged.

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:58.080
 It's like, oh, we built a little wall around the function

00:02:58.080 --> 00:02:59.920
 and nothing inside the function happens.

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.880
 The outside world is unaffected by it.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:06.400
 And that's a great oversimplification of call by value.

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:08.440
 Of course, call by reference means the stuff

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:11.240
 you do in this function can affect outside the function.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:14.720
 But let's talk a little bit about how a stack is used

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:16.520
 to accomplish this.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:19.280
 So just to use some terminology,

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:24.040
 C calls these variables that are allocated inside the function

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:28.400
 before the function starts as the automatic variables.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:31.340
 And frankly, int MA equals 42 in main

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:33.720
 is an automatic variable inside the main

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.800
 'cause main is a function inside a C program

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.800
 that happens to be the one that starts everything out.

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:43.440
 So if we get to the point where it says int MA equals 42

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.720
 and then it prints MA being 42,

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:49.800
 at that point on the stack, the C runtime

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.880
 has allocated one integer and we've assigned 42 to it.

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:55.880
 So that's what the stack looks like

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:58.080
 at that first print statement in main.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:02.200
 Then we call the function one and pass MA in.

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:04.760
 And this is where the C runtime library

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:09.760
 kind of before everything starts out in the function one,

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:13.000
 it allocates what's called a stack frame.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.720
 And a stack frame includes the parameters OP

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:21.820
 and the automatic variables that are inside of that function.

00:04:21.820 --> 00:04:24.680
 And so in this case, we're gonna get two variables.

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:28.560
 We're gonna get OP as an integer and TN as an integer.

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:30.760
 And before the program starts up,

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:35.760
 the value 42 is copied from MA into OP.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:38.280
 And so the stack frame is the context

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:41.400
 in which that function operates.

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:44.520
 So when it first starts, you see that OP has 42.

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:47.280
 You also see we have two copies of the number 42

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:49.920
 and we have a parameter OP

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:53.920
 and then we have the automatic variable, the TN.

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:59.040
 Then the next line runs, okay?

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:01.000
 And at that point, OP is changed.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.440
 OP equals OP minus TN.

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:05.360
 And so OP becomes 32.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.000
 But you'll notice that on the stack,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.080
 beyond the stack frame,

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:13.080
 the stack frame is our current execution of the function one.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:15.040
 Beyond the stack frame, the 42 is still there.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:15.960
 We can't see it.

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:18.040
 We're in the function right now

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.120
 and we're only seeing the top part of the stack.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:21.440
 We're not seeing the part of the stack

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.540
 that belongs to the main program.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:25.640
 So that's where it prints out 32.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:30.000
 So 32 in the function says OP is 32 and that's fine.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.800
 And then we return and that's when the C Runtime

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.280
 removes the stack frame, pops those things off the stack.

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:39.960
 It remembers how much it put on and it pops all the stuff

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:41.840
 off the stack that it put on.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:44.680
 And then it's basically comes back into MA

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:47.740
 and the stack frame for the main program

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:51.000
 has one variable in it and it's MA and it has 42.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.640
 And that's because one operated in its stack frame

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:57.280
 and now the main program is back to operating

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:58.560
 in the same stack frame.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:03.560
 You can almost think of this as like one never happened.

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:07.160
 From main's perspective, it had some variables.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:09.360
 One ran and a stack frame was created.

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:12.540
 Some of the main data was copied into the one stack frame.

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:14.760
 One operated in its stack frame.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:18.100
 And then the stack frame went away right before one

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:20.400
 or right at the moment that one returned.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.440
 And the return value ends up in the stack frame too.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:23.960
 I just haven't shown you that

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.080
 and these don't send return value.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:29.400
 So the return value comes back from the stack frame.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:32.400
 But you can see how main started with the stack

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:36.120
 with one variable on it and then it one ran

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:39.080
 and all that stuff happened and then it kind of was undone.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:40.720
 And that's where the changed variable

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:42.520
 just kind of went away.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:44.880
 And so the stack, it's as if nothing ever happened

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:47.120
 except it went up and then it went back down.

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:51.720
 Now one thing we notice and in Python we see this too

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:53.900
 where you say everything is called by value

00:06:53.900 --> 00:06:58.880
 which implies a copy except for things like certain objects

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:00.880
 and calling methods and objects.

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:03.560
 And if, but if you look at say this function zap

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:08.560
 and we pass in X and X starts out as original

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:12.480
 and then it calls the zap function and it passes in

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:14.360
 and it's got the original then it gets changed

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:19.360
 inside the zap function and that change prints out.

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:23.700
 But then when it comes back, it is back to the original.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:26.280
 So X is back to the original in the main code.

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:27.640
 And you might say, oh, that looks right.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:29.260
 And that's actually quite intuitive

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:33.800
 and that Python has made it so a call by value

00:07:33.800 --> 00:07:37.600
 inside of this call by value to the zap function.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:40.640
 It happened, meaning that nothing changed

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:42.480
 outside of the zap function.

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:44.560
 And it was a call by value, not a call by reference.

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:48.040
 Now, I'm not gonna go into it at least not right now

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.800
 talking about why that really worked.

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:52.520
 And it's less about call by value and call by reference

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:56.360
 and more about the fact that Y is really a pointer

00:07:56.360 --> 00:07:57.200
 to an object.

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:00.320
 And when Y equals changed executes inside of zap

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.040
 the object pointer, it points to a different object

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:04.960
 and then, but X never changed.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:08.440
 And so Python has a slightly different runtime

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:11.440
 but it leads to this notion that seems like

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:16.440
 a string variable in Python is call by value.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:19.800
 Now, if we look at the similar

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:23.680
 but quite different code inside of C,

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:27.520
 we see the main has a character array X

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.480
 of unknown length, which is original.

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:32.760
 And that just unknown length means that it says,

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:36.280
 it's looks like eight characters plus a backslash zero

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:37.900
 which is nine characters.

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:40.480
 And it prints out kind of like a string.

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:42.480
 It's a character array with a terminator.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:46.920
 And then we call zap pass X in.

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:51.560
 And then inside of zap, zap takes a character array

00:08:51.560 --> 00:08:54.480
 as its parameter and it can print out the word original

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:58.920
 when it starts and then it copies changed into it.

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:02.760
 And then it says at the end, it's Y is at the end

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:05.080
 is changed, but then we come back

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:07.940
 and back in the main program, it got changed.

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:12.180
 So does that mean it was called by reference or what?

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:18.220
 And the answer is sort of, and this is where it kind of helps.

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:21.200
 So it turns out that when you are passing

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:26.200
 an array into a function in C,

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:30.360
 you're not actually passing the contents of the array.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.740
 So most of the time we think of that 42 being copied

00:09:32.740 --> 00:09:34.660
 if it's an integer, if it's just like a scalar thing

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.120
 like a float or an enter char or something

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:38.520
 that's being copied.

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:40.680
 But when you have an array that could be gigantic.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:44.240
 So it doesn't actually copy in the whole array.

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:49.240
 So when X is being passed into zap and being received as Y,

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.920
 we're not actually passing the string

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:54.360
 'cause that could be a million characters for all we know.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:56.380
 So it's not like it makes an extra copy

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:57.680
 of a million characters.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:02.220
 What it's doing is it's passing in the address

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:03.960
 of the start of the string,

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.040
 not on the stack, but somewhere else.

00:10:06.040 --> 00:10:08.940
 It actually could be on the stack somewhere,

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:11.520
 but it's not in the stack frame

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:15.480
 and the word original is not copied into the stack frame.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:17.800
 The stack frame only includes a pointer

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:22.080
 or the address, X is the address of the letter O

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:24.840
 and then Y is also the address of the letter O,

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.580
 which means when we're calling str copy,

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.840
 we are overriding those characters.

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:32.260
 Oh, and by the way, I carefully made sure

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:34.120
 that the string changed was shorter

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:37.060
 than the string original or my program could have blown up

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:41.720
 because this is C and arrays don't get bigger.

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:45.680
 Python strings get bigger, but arrays don't.

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:48.600
 In a couple more lectures, we will build a data structure

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:52.200
 where it's like a Python string and we can add to it

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:55.560
 and you'll see that the code is very complex.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:10:59.360
 A character array is very simple, okay?

00:10:59.360 --> 00:11:04.360
 And so it's not exactly a pass by reference.

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:07.500
 It is a pass by location.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:10.040
 And if you happen to misuse that location,

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:13.320
 meaning you write to that location, you write to location.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:15.560
 Now this might've been in like read only memory something,

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:16.720
 your program might've blown up.

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:19.440
 So you better be sure what you're doing

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.680
 when you start messing inside of a function

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:23.840
 with an array that's been passed to you.

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:25.240
 Now sometimes you're supposed to.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:27.200
 Sometimes we tell you to write that.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:29.840
 Another thing that you're gonna see in this

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.240
 is the reference to register variables.

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:35.160
 This is another rather historical notion.

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:39.760
 And in my opinion, it really had to do with convincing

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:42.520
 really skilled assembly language programmers

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:45.440
 that they could get the same performance out of C

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:48.040
 that they were used to getting inside assembly language.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:49.760
 And so what are registers?

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:53.080
 Well, when you have a central processing unit

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:55.800
 and you have memory, the data lives in the memory

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:57.840
 and the registers live in the central processing unit.

00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.520
 And depending on the speed of things,

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:04.440
 a register might be 40 times faster than regular memory.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:08.960
 And so if you could keep a variable like i in a loop,

00:12:08.960 --> 00:12:11.680
 you could keep that in a register that's faster.

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:14.880
 And so what we can do with saying register int x is say,

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:16.880
 hey, by the way, next few lines,

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:18.520
 x is a really important variable

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:19.920
 and I expect to use it a lot.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:23.800
 So if you can possibly not store this in memory,

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:24.760
 please do so.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.000
 And that's why the only kind of weird thing

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.440
 about the register is you can't get the memory address

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:30.680
 of a register variable.

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:32.980
 Now in modern compilers,

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:36.440
 we have runtime optimizers that are miraculous.

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:37.760
 I mean, they border on miraculous,

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.820
 even the simplest of runtime optimizers

00:12:39.820 --> 00:12:42.920
 that speed the code up at runtime are miraculous.

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:46.400
 And saying this is a register or that's a register

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:48.720
 might actually confuse things.

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:50.480
 So all the register does is hey,

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:53.240
 I am never gonna ask you the address of this variable.

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:54.800
 So don't bother putting it in memory

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:56.400
 if you don't feel like it.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:58.160
 Okay, and so it's probably,

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:01.600
 but I also think it's kind of fascinating and fun

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:03.640
 to think about this.

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:08.640
 Think about how early C developers were so deeply connected

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:11.720
 to their assembly language that is at the runtime.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:16.140
 Recursion, recursion, recursion, recursion.

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:19.720
 When a function calls itself, it's called recursion.

00:13:19.720 --> 00:13:22.640
 It's a powerful, it's a beautiful concept.

00:13:22.640 --> 00:13:26.660
 There is places when if you're given a tree-like structure,

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:28.480
 like you parse some XML or something

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:30.720
 and you're reading through the XML,

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:34.860
 recursion is such a pretty way to write code.

00:13:34.860 --> 00:13:38.800
 I'm about to show you a very simple recursion example

00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:40.440
 that are two things.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:43.920
 First, they're really inefficient and silly uses

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:46.040
 of recursion and they mislead you

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:47.920
 as to why you should use recursion.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:50.120
 And they misleadingly kind of tell you that like,

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:52.320
 recursion is great, let's use it for something

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:54.460
 it is not well used for.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:59.480
 So really in this section, I'm not trying to show you

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:02.600
 what recursion is used for well.

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:05.080
 I'm more interested in giving you a really

00:14:06.560 --> 00:14:11.560
 artificial synthetic example to show how the call stack works

00:14:11.560 --> 00:14:15.640
 and how recursion works with the call stack.

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.720
 So here we have, I mean some tortured code.

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:22.080
 It is not pretty code.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:27.080
 This is a, I'm writing code that if given a number like three,

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:30.800
 adds up one plus two plus three, okay?

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:32.200
 And gives me six.

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:33.960
 There are so many ways to do this.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:35.300
 There's even a closed form solution

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:39.020
 that doesn't even require a loop that's called algebra.

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:40.920
 But we're going to use recursion.

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:46.840
 So if you look at the int main, I'm gonna say sum up three.

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:49.720
 That means sum up things one, two, three.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:51.520
 So sum up is being called from main

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:53.900
 and then I've got the return value and I say sup.

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:55.640
 And you'll notice in the printout

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:58.400
 that sup is the very last thing that comes out.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:03.000
 And so if you walk through sum up,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.680
 you see that there is a parameter called above

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:07.120
 that's coming, I call that above

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:09.200
 'cause it's coming from whoever's calling us.

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:11.680
 There's a parameter below which is we're gonna compute

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:14.920
 a value and send it down to the next copy of ourselves down.

00:15:14.920 --> 00:15:18.800
 And then sum is the sum of the above value

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:21.040
 and the sum of the below values.

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:25.520
 And then retval is, I mean actually sum is just coming back

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:26.840
 from the call to ourselves.

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:29.600
 And then retval is adding those two things together.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:32.820
 And I do this in exceedingly slow motion

00:15:32.820 --> 00:15:34.000
 with print statements everywhere

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:35.680
 that just makes us look ugly

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:37.320
 because really the only thing that matters

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.680
 is where it says sum equals sum up below.

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:44.280
 And what we're doing is we're calling the same function again.

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:47.280
 So if you look in main and you see the sum up call,

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:50.360
 that is going to create a stack frame.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:51.640
 And in that stack frame,

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:54.280
 it's gonna have whatever the three number is.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:55.640
 We're gonna make an above variable,

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:57.520
 copy three into the above variable

00:15:57.520 --> 00:15:59.720
 and allocate it below sum and retval.

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:03.080
 So our stack frame is gonna have four integers on it.

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:05.680
 And then the function starts working.

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:08.140
 And the way the recursion works

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:10.660
 is there's always gotta be a time at which it stops.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:12.560
 This is kind of like going down, down, down

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:14.360
 and then has to work its way back up.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.060
 If it goes down forever, that's called a stack overflow.

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:18.600
 And then your computer runs out of memory

00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:19.760
 and your application blows up.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:24.760
 So you have to have a time at which the stack algorithm stops.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:28.360
 So what we're saying is if we're being told

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:31.000
 to sum up one or less,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.880
 well, we define the sum of that as one.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.340
 So we just return the sum of everything up to one as one.

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:39.800
 And that's our way of stopping the recursion at the bottom.

00:16:39.800 --> 00:16:41.360
 And then what we do is we take below

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:42.480
 and we subtract one from it.

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:45.240
 So if we're being called with three, below becomes two.

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:47.700
 And so you see that over in the lower stack frame,

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:50.540
 below is two, right?

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:53.160
 Below is two and we're about to go down

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:55.360
 deeper into the call tree.

00:16:55.360 --> 00:17:00.320
 And so we're gonna call sum equals sum up below.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:03.000
 So what happens now is we're passing two in

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.440
 to another stack frame.

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:07.220
 And so there's not really another copy of the code,

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:08.960
 but there's another stack frame.

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:13.280
 And so now we're calling sum up with two as the parameter.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:15.760
 That's our below, but then we see the stack frame.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:16.960
 And now this is the stack frame

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:19.080
 that's kind of on the left-hand side there.

00:17:19.080 --> 00:17:22.000
 Above in this stack frame is two.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:23.760
 And then execution begins

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:26.640
 and we subtract one from below.

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:28.720
 Well, above is not less than one.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:33.140
 So we subtract one and below becomes one

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:34.800
 because it's two minus one.

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:35.820
 And we're going to go down.

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:38.840
 So it says down one, which means it's going to, again,

00:17:38.840 --> 00:17:41.320
 say sum equals sum up below.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:43.640
 And below in this case is one.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:46.980
 And so it makes another stack frame.

00:17:46.980 --> 00:17:50.800
 So we're actually, there is a maximum of like three calls

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:52.560
 here and then it's gonna work its way out.

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:55.400
 So then it calls another stack frame

00:17:55.400 --> 00:17:57.800
 that's not shown on the right-hand side.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:00.480
 And then it runs with one as above

00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:02.120
 and then above is less than or equal to one.

00:18:02.120 --> 00:18:02.960
 So it returns one.

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:04.760
 And that's why it says in one.

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:07.440
 And it doesn't say anything because then it's returned

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:09.220
 and it returned the value one.

00:18:09.220 --> 00:18:12.960
 So now the third stack frame comes off.

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:15.520
 And now we're in the other stack frame and sum

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:18.320
 is what the return value of the sum up call was.

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:22.080
 So it says back one, and then it says above.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:24.840
 Now we're in the stack frame that's on the right-hand side.

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:27.960
 So sum is one, below is one, above is two.

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:31.520
 And so we compute retval, which is one plus two,

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:32.640
 and that's three.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:35.840
 And we print that out and that's kinda where we're indicating.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:40.220
 And then we return the three, right?

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:43.200
 And then it returns retval and it runs some more.

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:47.640
 It gets three back, then it adds the three to it

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:50.640
 and returns one more time and the stack all pops up.

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:52.360
 And eventually you get six.

00:18:52.360 --> 00:18:57.620
 And this is a, you can look at this as long as you like.

00:18:57.620 --> 00:19:03.560
 This code is like a foolish way to make this calculation

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:07.640
 like most artificial recursion examples.

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:11.080
 But the key thing here is just think about the stack frame.

00:19:11.080 --> 00:19:14.340
 Every time you call in, another stack frame happens.

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:15.640
 Call in, stack frame happens.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:17.040
 And then when the return value happens,

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:18.800
 it goes back to that stack frame.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:21.680
 So the stack frame is a way of pausing execution

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:23.880
 at the moment, create a new stack frame,

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:26.320
 execute in that stack frame, and if you need to,

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:27.840
 have a yet another stack frame.

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:30.640
 And so this idea of creating a stack frame

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:32.400
 with the parameters and automatic variables,

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.040
 each time you call a function,

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:36.040
 copying the parameters into that stack frame,

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:38.640
 and then executing the function in that stack frame.

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:41.440
 We're not making extra copies of the function,

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:43.840
 we are just creating a new stack frame.

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:48.240
 That's what the essence of recursion is,

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:50.280
 is the fact that you have a stack,

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:52.680
 and each call makes a stack frame,

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:54.200
 and if you recursively call again,

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:56.560
 you just make another stack frame.

00:19:56.560 --> 00:19:58.840
 And so it's almost easier in my mind

00:19:58.840 --> 00:20:01.860
 to think through how stack frames work

00:20:01.860 --> 00:20:04.880
 than it is to think through how recursive code works.

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:08.760
 Now, I wanna talk a little bit about the C preprocessor.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.400
 It's the last thing in this chapter,

00:20:11.400 --> 00:20:13.020
 and it's in some ways orthogonal

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:14.460
 to functions and program structure.

00:20:14.460 --> 00:20:16.420
 I mean, it is part of program structure.

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:21.040
 And so I've talked a lot about how wonderfully

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:24.680
 the C compiler, and eventually Unix,

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:29.740
 solved so many problems of software source code portability.

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:33.780
 And things like endianess, and character arrays,

00:20:33.780 --> 00:20:36.960
 and masking and shifting not being necessary,

00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:38.440
 that those were awesome.

00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:39.960
 But the problem was is that

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:43.600
 C has always operated in an environment.

00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:44.940
 The language has changed.

00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:49.800
 In the early days, it wasn't standardized.

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:53.400
 By '84, it got standardized, ANSI-C came out.

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:56.360
 A lot of people used it outside its original creation,

00:20:56.360 --> 00:20:57.880
 and so a lot of things got fixed

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:00.480
 in the first decade of C's use.

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:02.160
 The language evolved a lot.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:03.880
 The language kept evolving,

00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:05.920
 and a lot of the things that would make it evolve

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:08.840
 are things like integers went from 32 bits

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:11.120
 in some situations to 64 bits,

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:14.200
 and then you have to say, well, what is a long?

00:21:14.200 --> 00:21:16.600
 It's long 64, long 32.

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:19.080
 'Cause it started with int being 16 bits,

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:22.280
 and long being 32, and then long was 64.

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:25.160
 Well, for a while, then ints were 32, and longs were 32,

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:28.480
 and then ints were 32, and longs were 64,

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:30.680
 and what would happen if ints were 64?

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:33.480
 And it had to do with computer architecture, 64 bits, right?

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:38.140
 And so sometimes you would have a bit of code,

00:21:38.140 --> 00:21:41.920
 and you knew you wanted a 32-bit thing,

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:44.020
 and you weren't sure if an int or a long or a short

00:21:44.020 --> 00:21:45.320
 was gonna give you 32.

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.880
 And so you had to say, you know,

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:48.480
 I really need different source code.

00:21:48.480 --> 00:21:52.400
 Like if I'm working on a PDP-11, I got one thing,

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:54.080
 and if I'm working on an Interdata-7-32,

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:58.360
 I want another thing, 'cause really I want a 32-bit integer.

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:00.680
 And now there's actually int-32 in some of these things

00:22:00.680 --> 00:22:02.360
 'cause you do need to know sometimes

00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:04.120
 you're using 32-bit integer.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:05.680
 Then libraries changed.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:08.840
 There's calling sequences that changed because, again,

00:22:08.840 --> 00:22:10.160
 as computers got bigger and bigger,

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:12.680
 and memory got bigger, and disk drives got bigger,

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:15.440
 you would be in a certain version of an operating system,

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:19.720
 and the calls to reading files might be slightly different.

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:22.600
 And so it's not really that the source code was portable.

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:26.540
 It's the calling sequences to libraries started to change.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:30.360
 Hardware evolved, operating systems evolved.

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:32.320
 C started running on non-UNIX

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:34.320
 because C originally started on UNIX,

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:37.120
 but then it quickly went to other operating systems

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:38.880
 'cause it was such a powerful concept.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:41.540
 But sometimes in these other operating systems,

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:43.000
 just things were kind of different

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:44.640
 because they weren't working on UNIX.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:48.640
 And so the preprocessor really was an effective way

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:51.360
 to patch your source code so that you could say,

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:53.400
 look, I wrote this source code 10 years ago,

00:22:53.400 --> 00:22:55.860
 and it worked on a PDP-11,

00:22:55.860 --> 00:22:59.980
 and now I'm gonna run this on an IBM 360 architecture,

00:22:59.980 --> 00:23:02.120
 and I don't want to change,

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:04.760
 that there's a few changes I need to make

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:08.080
 that have nothing to do with what a for loop looks like,

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:10.440
 but it has to do with like what library I'm calling

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:13.240
 or what the return type for that library might be.

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:17.880
 So the preprocessor allowed us to put variations

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:18.740
 in the source code.

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:21.760
 And the preprocessor, it really feels weird

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:24.720
 'cause its syntax is very different

00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:28.040
 because the preprocessor is kind of a line-oriented processor

00:23:28.040 --> 00:23:30.800
 and it has these pound things, right?

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:35.800
 These like pound if def, pound define, pound else,

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:38.060
 pound end if, and pound include.

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:40.500
 That's even a preprocessor.

00:23:40.500 --> 00:23:43.900
 So what the preprocessor is, is not a compiler at all.

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:47.260
 It is a source code to source code translator.

00:23:47.260 --> 00:23:50.520
 It expands the include files, and then it makes changes.

00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:54.560
 So in the top example where you see pound include stdio.h,

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.240
 you can actually run GCC minus capital E,

00:23:57.240 --> 00:23:59.240
 and it says just run the preprocessor

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:00.720
 and shows me what comes out.

00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:04.040
 You take 10, 12 lines of code on the left

00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:07.120
 and it puts out hundreds and hundreds of lines of code

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:07.960
 on the right.

00:24:07.960 --> 00:24:09.480
 I'm just showing you a subset of it.

00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:12.560
 But the biggest part is the fact that include stdio.h

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:14.980
 is literally expanded.

00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:18.640
 And then that is C code without the pound include, okay?

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:20.160
 So that's the preprocessor.

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:21.760
 But then another example here

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:24.700
 is I'm creating this use_long.

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:26.040
 This is not really a variable.

00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:28.340
 This is a compile time variable.

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:32.300
 So I'm gonna create a new string called int_32,

00:24:32.300 --> 00:24:35.540
 and if use_long has been defined,

00:24:35.540 --> 00:24:37.880
 I'm gonna make int32 be a long.

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:40.920
 Else, I'm gonna make int_32 be an int.

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.160
 And again, this could be a thing

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:44.060
 where I'm compiling for different architectures,

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:49.060
 and I want this variable IP address to be a 32-bit integer,

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:52.260
 and I need it to work on different operating systems.

00:24:52.260 --> 00:24:58.000
 So in this case, because use_long is not defined,

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.380
 int32 as a string substitution,

00:25:00.380 --> 00:25:01.980
 like a macro string substitution

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:04.360
 before the compiler even does anything,

00:25:04.360 --> 00:25:06.760
 turns int32 into int.

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:10.400
 And so that's what the five lines of pound if def

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:12.080
 and all that stuff do is it says

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:16.960
 change this int32 string in my source code into int.

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:20.200
 And so what we see on the right is really C code.

00:25:20.200 --> 00:25:24.760
 What we see on the left is kind of preprocessor plus C code.

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:28.360
 And so the preprocessor transforms source code

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:29.200
 to source code.

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:32.280
 So I was looking around at some old code

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:36.000
 that I happened to have grabbed and put into GitHub,

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:40.880
 which was some code from 1994 from XMosaic 1.2.

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:43.000
 And for those of you who took my internet history,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:43.880
 technology and security,

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:48.520
 you know that XMosaic was the first web browser

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:51.720
 that was portable across multiple operating systems.

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:54.240
 And the more, and then eventually Mosaic ended up

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:56.760
 on Unix systems with X windows,

00:25:56.760 --> 00:25:58.320
 that's why it's called XMosaic,

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:00.100
 and it went to the Mac and went to the PC.

00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:03.920
 And so it was really many Unixes, Mac and PC.

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:06.120
 And what we're seeing here on the right-hand side

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:08.080
 is actual source code from that,

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:10.960
 which was written in like 1993, 1994.

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:14.640
 And what you see is a bunch of if-defs and if-end-defs

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:17.640
 and some comments and like there's an if-defs,

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:19.120
 hilarious nine broken.

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:20.960
 And it has to do with like,

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:23.480
 where do we find the error messages on this

00:26:23.480 --> 00:26:26.740
 across all these weird operating systems?

00:26:26.740 --> 00:26:28.520
 'Cause the way they put error messages,

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:30.000
 sometimes they would use extern,

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.200
 which are global variables defined inside the runtime.

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:34.760
 And we would just look at those variables.

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.280
 We would make a function call

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:38.680
 and it would write into these global variables.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:40.880
 But then that global variable might be different.

00:26:40.880 --> 00:26:45.880
 So this is actually from some code that was HTTP and C.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:49.580
 That was some early network connections.

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:51.600
 Now these days, you know, we just do this stuff

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:54.920
 in like the pound import requests in Python.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:58.320
 But in those days, the C libraries for network connections

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:01.600
 were really different, meaning that they were just,

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:02.780
 you know, here comes the network,

00:27:02.780 --> 00:27:05.840
 here's this language C, it's been around by, you know,

00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:10.320
 89, 90, 91, the network was there.

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:11.800
 And so we were building libraries,

00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:14.400
 but then how each library worked in each operating system

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:16.200
 was a little wonky.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:20.800
 And so they had to write different C code to compensate

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:24.400
 for the different operating systems that this C program,

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:27.560
 a web browser would be running on.

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:30.860
 And so all these if-defs mean that one source code

00:27:30.860 --> 00:27:35.820
 with a few predefined constants, compile time constants,

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:39.560
 could then work on a wide range of operating systems.

00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:43.280
 And so yes, the C language itself is portability, portable,

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:46.380
 but we also wanna be portable over time.

00:27:46.380 --> 00:27:50.900
 And so sometimes libraries change, operating systems change,

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:54.200
 and we want to be able to compensate for that.

00:27:54.200 --> 00:27:56.880
 And so this is an important part of C.

00:27:56.880 --> 00:27:59.640
 These days, it's less important

00:27:59.640 --> 00:28:02.020
 because a lot of the libraries have stabilized

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:03.600
 and they don't change quite so much.

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:06.040
 And so this code here would probably just be

00:28:06.040 --> 00:28:08.240
 a bit of socket code and the errors would come back

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:10.680
 the same way, no matter what version.

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:15.680
 Like VMS is an operating system that doesn't exist anymore.

00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:19.000
 ThinkC doesn't exist anymore.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.960
 Next doesn't exist anymore.

00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:22.880
 Solaris doesn't exist anymore.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:24.160
 So these are all operating systems

00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:25.760
 that don't even exist anymore.

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:28.560
 But this code was portable across all those things.

00:28:28.560 --> 00:28:30.360
 And actually, I compiled all this

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:31.760
 and you can kinda take a look at it.

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:35.600
 I made a video where I resurrected this code,

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:37.340
 oh, it's gotta be eight or nine years ago,

00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:41.200
 on a Macintosh, which is evolved from Next.

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:42.760
 I don't know if I could get it to work again,

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:45.360
 but back then I got it to work on a Macintosh

00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:48.320
 and I said, defined it as Next.

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:50.740
 And so I compiled the C code,

00:28:50.740 --> 00:28:53.520
 and there is an X Windows on Macintosh,

00:28:53.520 --> 00:28:55.980
 so I got the X Windows library, got all this stuff working,

00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:59.720
 and I told it, you're a Next, and I recompiled the C code,

00:28:59.720 --> 00:29:01.400
 and eventually something came up.

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:04.000
 And I made a video about it,

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.340
 because I knew that it'd be very difficult

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:09.080
 to keep this thing working over time.

00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:13.080
 But to go from 1994 to 2014

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:17.120
 and recompile something 20 years later,

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:18.400
 that's still pretty impressive,

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:20.720
 that Next code would still work.

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:23.280
 Things like the VM code, VMS code,

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:26.840
 there's no VMS computers that I know of these days.

00:29:26.840 --> 00:29:32.760
 So it just shows that the idea of portability is a,

00:29:32.760 --> 00:29:39.320
 some of it is simple and elegant,

00:29:39.320 --> 00:29:41.960
 and was laid down in 1978,

00:29:41.960 --> 00:29:44.400
 but then there are things outside the programming language

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:48.040
 that were evolving, and still are evolving to this day.

00:29:48.040 --> 00:29:51.120
 And if you are doing C coding today,

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:53.960
 or C++ coding today, you may be using things

00:29:53.960 --> 00:29:54.960
 that start with pound sign,

00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:59.960
 which are compiler directives, rather than C code.

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:05.160
 So, with that, dive into chapter four,

00:30:05.160 --> 00:30:07.520
 and learn about functions.

00:30:07.520 --> 00:30:10.100
